[1] Brazil (Roraima)
Date:18 Sep 2003 00:00:12
From: Marilda Milagres <net_milagres@fclnet.com.br>
Source: Folha de Boa Vista 17 Set 2003 [in Portuguese, summarized by
Mod.JW] [edited]
<http://portalamazonia.globo.com/apresenta-noticias.php?idN=2896&idLingua=1>

Data from the Municipal Health Secretary show that as of Fri 12 Sep
2003, 4551 cases of dengue were notified in the city of Boa Vista, of
which 2170 have been confirmed. This is 59 percent fewer cases than
during 2002.
******
[2] China (Hong Kong)
Date: 22 Sep 2003
From: ProMED <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Hong Kong Department of Health 22 Sep 2003 [edited]
<http://www.info.gov.hk/dh/diseases/index.htm>

The Department of Health (DH) today, 22 Sep 2003, confirmed one more
imported case of dengue fever and urged members of the public to
guard against the disease.
Case details are as follows: 54-year-old female, onset 13 Sep 2003 of
fever, mild headache and eye pain, recovered and discharged from
hospital. Travelled to a Southeast Asian country and a South Asian
country from 16-24 Sep 2003.
Cumulative total for dengue in 2003: imported 38, local 0.
******
[3] India (Gujarat)
Date: 22 Sep 2003
From: ProMED
Source: Times of India 17 Sep 2003 [edited]
<http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/>

A 60-year-old woman who was diagnosed as suffering from dengue fever
died here on Sunday at the Shardaben municipal hospital, Ahmedabad,
even as medical experts now feel that the mysterious fever that had
led to 6 deaths in a Gandhinagar village could have been dengue fever.
A 16-year-old boy suspected to be suffering from dengue fever also
died the same day at this hospital. Civil hospital superintendent Dr
Anil Chaddha could not confirm that the 6 deaths in Borisana village
of Gandhinagar were also due to dengue fever on the grounds that,
"the report of those tests are awaited."
Ahmedabad reported a few cases of dengue, while the 6 persons who
died in Borisana village of Gandhinagar district of a mysterious
fever and 75 patients were affected, also showed symptoms of dengue,
according to medical experts [see: Undiagnosed deaths - India
(Gujarat): RFI in refs. below].
Medical officer of health at the AMC Dr P. K. Makwana told TNN that a
dengue fever case was also diagnosed on 9 Sep 2003 in the city.
"Ahmedabad has seen a few cases of dengue fever this season. Better
diagnostic facilities in private pathology laboratories has now made
it possible to diagnose it," he said.
According to Makwana, AMC health officials have now started a mass
awareness campaign to educate people about the cause and symptoms of
dengue fever. "We have asked residents to ensure that all overhead
storage tanks are sealed with an airtight cover. We have also asked
people to regularly change water in air coolers etc," he said.
----
Date: 22 Sep 2003
From: ProMED
Source: Times of India 22 Sep 2003 [edited]
<http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/>

Medical professionals in Vadodara city are on high alert after 2
people died of the dreaded dengue fever recently. Another 8-10 cases
have been reported from various hospitals in the city. Most of the
cases reported are from Navayard, Wadi, Raopura, Tarsali and
Manjalpur. The deceased were children; a 3-year-old from Wadi and a
7-year-old from Navayard, who were admitted to KG Patel Children's
Hospital.
At the moment, about 5 cases are being treated at F. G. Patel and
Krishna Children's Critical Care Centre in the city. Says Dr Hitesh
Desai, a paediatrician at KG Patel Hospital, "Till now, we have had
about 6 dengue cases. The 2 patients who died were in a critical
condition. However, we have ICU facilities, which are crucial for
managing this disease. The patient needs round-the-clock monitoring."
"We have a confirmed case of dengue still undergoing treatment,
while one has been shifted back to Godhra. The patients need to be
kept under critical care monitoring, as most cases lead to
complications. As only presumptive diagnosis is possible, we are left
with no choice but to monitor hydration and blood pressure of the
patient," informs Dr Tushar Kulkarni of Krishna Children's Critical
Care Hospital.
The appearance of dengue in Vadodara has come as no surprise despite
the fact that it is usually found in the coastal region, say doctors.
"The city has a migrating population and moreover, the mosquito
species _Aedes aegypti_, which carries the dengue virus, is not new
to Vadodara. Vector control through elimination of mosquito breeding
sites and protection from mosquito bites can go a long way in disease
prevention," says Dr Satish Pandya, who presented a report on dengue
at a clinical meeting held recently.
The presence of dengue virus is confirmed through 2 tests: Viral
isolation and antibody titre tests. However, the pathological
laboratories in the city have only the antibody titre tests to
confirm the cases. Meanwhile the Vadodara Municipal Corporation has
informed all hospitals in the city to report the dengue cases as and
when admitted. "The VMC has directed us to report the cases so that
the samples could be despatched for viral isolation tests at Pune,"
informed Desai.
