[4] India (New Delhi)
Date: 22 Sep 2003
From: ProMED
Source: Times of India 20 Sep 2003 [edited]
<http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/>

4 patients suspected to be suffering from dengue fever, including
relatives of All India Institute of Medical Sciences (AIIMS)
employees, were admitted to the hospital on Thursday [18 Sep 2003].
New Delhi Medical Centre health officials confirmed the same.
Sources say 6 children of AIIMS employees, suspected to be suffering
from dengue, were admitted in the pediatrics ward on Thursday.
******
[5] India (South Delhi)
Date: 22 Sep 2003
From: ProMED
Source: Hindustan Times 20 Sep 2003 [edited]
<http://www.hindustantimes.com/>

At least 5 persons have died of suspected dengue in Jal Vihar near
Lajpat Nagar Central Market this month, and the Municipal Corporation
of Delhi (MCD) apparently came to know about it only on Friday. The
deceased had similar symptoms of high fever and died within 3-4 days
of falling ill.
On Saturday, the civic body ordered an inquiry into the deaths, all
of which have been reported from the "Madrasi Colony" of Jal Vihar.
The colony has more than 2500 jhuggis [slum dwellings] that line a
railway track amid heaps of filth and stagnated water.
The latest cases of suspected dengue deaths were reported on Friday.
2 people, including a 50-year-old railway employee, died in the area.
Residents said he had fallen ill about 3 days back and died early on
Friday. MCD health officer, Dr KN Tewari said none of the cases had
been reported to them till now. "The deaths probably did not occur in
hospitals who would have notified us. Another point is that dengue
deaths usually occur between 5 and 7 days, not within 3-4 days.
However, I have asked the deputy health officer of the zone to look
into the matter and give a report," Tewari told HT.
******
[6] India (Maharashtra)
Date: 22 Sep 2003
From: ProMED
Source: Xinhua 21 Sep 2003 [edited]

Health authorities have confirmed 9 cases of dengue in Nasik of west
India's Maharashtra state, 1222 km from New Delhi, according to the
Press Trust of India (PTI) Sunday. 56 blood samples were collected
from different parts of the city and sent to the National Virus
Research Laboratory in Pune of the state. 9 of them were found
positive, PTI reported.
The health department has reportedly examined 18 293 houses and also
given guidance to the citizens. A total of 10 535 containers were
examined, 173 of which were found with mosquito larvae. Notices have
also been issued to owners of septic tanks.
[These statistics are intriguing. On average apparently only about
50 percent of the houses inspected had a container that could breed
_Aedes aegypti_ mosquitoes, and 173 positive out of 10 535 containers
is an extraordinarily low number to sustain a dengue epidemic.
Perhaps they were all concentrated in one district, from which all
the dengue cases are coming? - Mod.JW]
******
[7] Indonesia (North Sumatra)
Date: 22 Sep 2003
From: ProMED
Source: Xinhua 19 Sep 2003 [edited]

An outbreak of dengue fever has hit several regencies in North
Sumatra in Indonesia this year, leaving at least 10 people, mostly
children, dead and 280 others hospitalized, the daily Jakarta Post
reported Friday.
The disease, carried by _Aedes aegypti_ mosquitoes, started to spread
last January [2003], but the 10 deaths were just recorded between
March and September [2003]. 2 of the deaths were reported on Tuesday
and Wednesday from the Sari Mutiara and Pirngadi hospitals in Medan,
the capital of North Sumatra.
According to data from the North Sumatra provincial health office,
the number of dengue fever cases stood at 280 between 15 Jan and
September 2003.
----
Date: 22 Sep 2003
From: ProMED <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Jakarta Post 20 Sep 2003 [edited]
<http://www.thejakartapost.com/yesterdaydetail.asp?fileid=20030920.D14>

2 more children were reported to have died from the outbreak of
dengue fever that has been plaguing several parts of North Sumatra,
bringing the death toll to at least 12 victims since March [2003].
Health officials said on Friday that the 2 children, P.B., 4, from
Satria village in Tebing Tinggi regency, and F., 5, from Medan, died
in local hospitals on Wednesday and Thursday, respectively. Syahrial
R. Anas, acting head of the Medan health office, said the children
died after suffering from severe hemorrhaging. In fact, the deaths
could have been prevented if the families of the victims had taken
the children to hospital immediately for treatment. "Parents can take
early measures by giving their infected children enough fluids and
anti-fever drugs so as to reduce their temperatures before bringing
them to the hospital," he told The Jakarta Post.
Responding to the controversy over the swallow aviaries that are
believed to be the breeding places of _Aedes aegypti_ mosquitoes in
the province, Syahrial said his office has sent a team to inspect 60
of the 600 such aviaries in Medan. The environmental health technical
center at the Medan health office recently found that 90 percent of
the swallow aviaries served as breeding places for the
disease-carrying mosquitoes. Swallows' nests, cemented together by
the birds' saliva, are used in traditional medicine and are a major
source of income in North Sumatra.
******
[8] Philippines (Marikina City)
Date: 22 Sep 2003
From: ProMED <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Manila Bulletin 12 Sep 2003 [edited]
<http://www.mb.com.ph/>

Marikina City health personnel and volunteers were directed yesterday
to continue the massive information drive in the 16 health centers as
well as public and private schools to drum up awareness among
residents to stop the spread of dengue fever within the Shoe Capital.
Mayor Marides C. Fernando issued the order after having been informed
that 55 cases of dengue have been reported by the City Health Office
(CHO) from 1 Jan - 31 Aug 2003. City health and sanitation officer
Ronald Dalusong said of the number, 85 percent were males with ages
15 years old and above.
DoH Secretary Manuel Dayrit said the National Epidemiology Center
(NEC) -- charged with monitoring the prevalence of the disease --
reported that at least 29 percent of dengue cases were detected in
Manila, 15 percent in Caloocan City, and 9 percent in Quezon City.
July and August are said to be the peak months of the disease and
likely to drop this current month [September] and October.
******
[9] Viet Nam (Ho Chi Minh City)
Date: 22 Sep 2003
From: ProMED
Source: Xinhua 18 Sep 2003 [edited]

As of 14 Sep 2003, as many as 2948 people in Vietnam's Ho Chi Minh
City were infected with dengue fever, up 71.8 percent against the
whole year of 2002, local newspaper Young People reported Friday.
The 2 main reasons are that the city is rainy and hot, and many
locals store rainwater in containers for domestic use, which create
favorable conditions for the development of mosquitoes. Most of
Vietnamese dengue fever patients live in the south of the country. As
of mid July [2003], over 12 000 people in the region were reported to
have been infected with the disease, a year-on-year increase of 164.6
percent.
